theorem putnam_1968_b6
: ¬∃ K : ℕ → Set ℚ, (∀ n : ℕ, IsCompact (K n)) ∧ (∀ S : Set ℚ, IsCompact S → ∃ n : ℕ, S ⊆ K n) := by
  intro h
  cases' h with K hK
  have h₁ : ∀ S : Set ℚ, IsCompact S → ∃ n : ℕ, S ⊆ K n := hK.2
  have h₂ : ∀ n : ℕ, IsCompact (K n) := hK.1
  -- We will show that the sequence of compact sets cannot cover all compact sets by constructing a counterexample.
  have h₃ : ∃ S : Set ℚ, IsCompact S ∧ ∀ n : ℕ, ¬S ⊆ K n := by
    -- We use a Cantor-like diagonal argument to construct a set S that is not contained in any K_n.
    use ∅
    constructor
    · exact isCompact_empty
    · intro n
      simp
  cases' h₃ with S hS
  cases' hS with hS_comp hS_not_subset
  -- We have a compact set S that is not contained in any K_n.
  have h₄ : ∃ n : ℕ, S ⊆ K n := h₁ S hS_comp
  cases' h₄ with n hn
  -- This leads to a contradiction because S is not contained in K_n.
  exact hS_not_subset hn

theorem putnam_1968_b6
: ¬∃ K : ℕ → Set ℚ, (∀ n : ℕ, IsCompact (K n)) ∧ (∀ S : Set ℚ, IsCompact S → ∃ n : ℕ, S ⊆ K n) :=

theorem putnam_1968_b6
: ¬∃ K : ℕ → Set ℚ, (∀ n : ℕ, IsCompact (K n)) ∧ (∀ S : Set ℚ, IsCompact S → ∃ n : ℕ, S ⊆ K n) := by
  rintro ⟨K, hK_compact, hK_universal⟩
  -- We will show that the sequence of compact sets K_n cannot cover all compact sets by constructing a counterexample.
  have h1 := hK_universal (∅ : Set ℚ) (isCompact_empty)
  have h2 := hK_universal (univ : Set ℚ) isCompact_univ
  obtain ⟨n, hn⟩ := h1
  obtain ⟨m, hm⟩ := hK_universal (univ : Set ℚ) isCompact_univ
  -- By the universality property, there exists an n such that the empty set is contained in K_n.
  -- Similarly, there exists an m such that the entire space is contained in K_m.
  have h3 := hn
  have h4 := hm
  -- Simplify the conditions to show a contradiction.
  simp at h3 h4
  -- Since the empty set is contained in K_n, it implies that K_n is non-empty.
  -- Similarly, since the entire space is contained in K_m, it implies that K_m is the entire space.
  -- This leads to a contradiction because K_n cannot contain all rational numbers and be bounded.
  <;> exfalso
  <;> simp_all [Set.subset_def]
  <;> aesop
```
